# Commit Conventions

All commits must follow the Conventional Commits specification.

## Format

```
<type>(<scope>): <subject>

<body>

<footer>
```

The header (`type(scope): subject`) is required. Scope is optional. Body and footer are optional but encouraged for non-trivial changes.

## Commit Types

| Type | Purpose | Example |
|------|---------|---------|
| `feat` | New feature | `feat(auth): Add OAuth2 PKCE flow` |
| `fix` | Bug fix | `fix(api): Handle null response in user endpoint` |
| `docs` | Documentation only | `docs: Update API usage guide` |
| `style` | Formatting, no logic change | `style: Apply consistent indentation` |
| `refactor` | Code restructuring, no behavior change | `refactor: Extract validation to shared module` |
| `perf` | Performance improvement | `perf(db): Add index on users.email` |
| `test` | Adding or correcting tests | `test(auth): Add login failure edge cases` |
| `build` | Build system or dependencies | `build: Upgrade Spring Boot to 3.3` |
| `ci` | CI configuration | `ci: Add parallel test execution` |
| `chore` | Maintenance, tooling | `chore: Update .gitignore` |
| `revert` | Reverting a previous commit | `revert: feat(api): Add new endpoint` |

## Subject Line Rules

- Use imperative, present tense: "Add feature" not "Added feature"
- Capitalize the first letter
- No period at the end
- Maximum 72 characters
- Be specific: "Add email validation to registration" not "Update code"

## Body Guidelines

- Explain **what** and **why**, not how
- Use imperative mood and present tense
- Wrap at 100 characters per line
- Include motivation and contrast with previous behavior when relevant
- Separate from subject with a blank line

## Footer Conventions

### Issue References

```
Fixes #1234
Fixes GH-1234
Refs LINEAR-ABC-123
```

- `Fixes` / `Closes` -- closes the issue when merged
- `Refs` -- links without closing

### Breaking Changes

```
feat(api)!: Remove deprecated v1 endpoints

BREAKING CHANGE: v1 endpoints are no longer available.
Clients must migrate to v2 endpoints before upgrading.
```

The `!` after the type/scope signals a breaking change. Always include a `BREAKING CHANGE:` footer with migration instructions.

### Co-Authorship

When changes were pair-programmed or AI-assisted:

```
Co-Authored-By: Name <email@example.com>
```

## Commit Principles

- Each commit must be a single, logical change
- The repository must build and pass tests after each commit
- Commits must be independently reviewable
- Prefer many small commits over one large commit
- Never mix formatting changes with logic changes
- Never mix refactoring with feature changes

## Revert Format

```
revert: <original commit subject>

This reverts commit <sha>.

Reason: <why the revert was necessary>
```

## Anti-Patterns

| Bad | Why | Better |
|-----|-----|--------|
| `fix: stuff` | Vague, unhelpful | `fix(auth): Return 401 for expired tokens` |
| `WIP` | Not a valid commit type | `feat(cart): Add item quantity validation (incomplete)` |
| `fix typo` | Missing type format | `docs: Fix typo in README installation steps` |
| `update code` | Meaningless | `refactor(api): Simplify error response builder` |
| Mixing features and fixes | Hard to review/revert | Separate into distinct commits |
